    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Less Popular Creatures</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Maura McClure letter comments on October 15 Week in Review article on decision by Agriculture Department to expand regulation of animals used in biomedical experiments</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What's Next? Rights for Mites?'' (Week in Review, Oct. 15), about the Department of Agriculture's recent decision to expand its regulation of animals used in biomedical experiments to include rats, mice and birds:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What's Next? Rights for Mites?'' (Week in Review, Oct. 15), about the Department of Agriculture's recent decision to expand its regulation of animals used in biomedical experiments to include rats, mice and birds:</p>
        <p>It's about time. Rats and mice account for 90 percent of the animals used in medical experiments, and they deserve as much protection as any other animal. After all, all animals can experience pain and fear, regardless of what size they are -- or how popular they are.</p>
        <p>MAURA MC CLURE  Virginia Beach, Oct. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
